<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-576-318  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 576 318.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  August 29 1989 n1251* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Nippon Telegraph andamp; Telephone specifies Tron for ISDN equipment.andO;(US firms complain)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (contracts).andO;Product:   TRON (Operating system) (usage).andO;Topic:     SpecificationsJapanese CompetitionInternational TradeTelephone SystemsSwitching CentersISDNApplicationsContracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NIPPON TELEGRAPH andamp; TELEPHONE SPECIFIES TRONandM;FOR ISDN EQUIPMENTandM;US companies are complaining that Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp'sspecification of the Tron operating system as mandatory for its ISDN anddigital switching network suppliers is a trade barrier against US firmshoping to bid for contracts.andP;  But NTT officials claimed that Tron was an opensystem, available for development by foreign as well as Japanese firms.andO;However, the Japanese have now built up a long lead in Tron expertise becauseforeign companies ignored the operating system, dismissing it as an academicgizmo that would never fly in the commercial world.andP;  As a result, in thecurrent joint development effort to build systems for Tron at NTT, NorthernTelecom Ltd is the only outsider company.andP;  The others are Fujitsu Ltd,Hitachi Ltd, Matsushita Electric Industrial Co, Mitsubishi Electric Corp, NECCorp, Oki Electric Co and Toshiba Corp. Nippon Telegraph plans to use Tron onits DEX digital network switching processor and in the ISDN interfacesubscriber module that is to be added to the existing D-70 public telephoneexchange to provide ISDN support over analogue telephone networks, ElectronicNews reports from Tokyo.andP;  Nippon Telegraph has been experimenting with animplementation of Tron on Motorola 68000 family microprocessors, althoughthese will not be used in the first versions of the new ISDN equipment.andO;</